# Problems Practiced

## 1. Largest Element

### Logic

* Assume first element is largest.
* Traverse array.
* Update max whenever a larger element is found.

```javascript
function largestNum(arr){

    let max = arr[0];

    for(let i = 1; i < arr.length; i++){
        if(arr[i] > max){
            max = arr[i];
        }
    }

    return max;
}
```

---

## 2. Reverse Array

### Logic

* Start from last index.
* Traverse backwards.

```javascript
function reverse(arr){

    for(let i = arr.length - 1; i >= 0; i--){
        console.log(arr[i]);
    }
}
```

---

## 3. Count Frequency

### Logic

* Create empty object.
* Traverse array.
* Count occurrences.

```javascript
function countFrequency(arr){

    let freq = {};

    for(let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++){

        if(freq[arr[i]]){
            freq[arr[i]]++;
        }else{
            freq[arr[i]] = 1;
        }
    }

    return freq;
}
```

# Key Takeaways

1. Arrays store multiple values.
2. Objects store data as key-value pairs.
3. Use loops to traverse arrays.
4. `push()` is the most commonly used array method.
5. Arrays and Objects are used together in almost every JavaScript project.
6. Real-world data from APIs usually comes as Arrays of Objects.

